## Edge cases

- **Single-seed counterfactuals.** Reject by design. The skill refuses to
  produce a `REPORT.md` from an ensemble below the minimum floor.
- **Pairing illusions.** If "paired-run discipline" is claimed but the two
  arms used different event-stream draws or different initial conditions,
  the pairing is fake. Audit the manifest before aggregating.
- **Multiple-comparisons inflation.** Sensitivity analysis runs many
  comparisons. Report the headline at one outcome × one window; treat the
  sweep as exploratory and flag any cherry-picked grid point.
- **Calibration-dependent results.** If the headline Δ flips when the
  calibration uses the held-out window from `/sim-calibrate`, document
  the flip prominently in `SENSITIVITY.md` and `REPORT.md`. Do not bury.
- **Regime breaks.** A calibrated sim on pre-2020 data evaluated on a
  2020+ counterfactual is extrapolation. Surface it.
- **Confounded interventions.** If the intervention requires changing
  more than one variable to be coherent (e.g., a rate hike implies a
  reaction-function change), document the joint intervention and run it
  as the joint; do not run only the rate change and ignore the rule.
- **Event-stream mutations that violate observability.** A counterfactual
  that removes an event from the past must respect the observability-time
  model — agents who would have reacted to the event must un-react in a
  way consistent with their information sets. Defer to
  `/event-stream OBSERVABILITY-MAP.md` for the mutation rule.

